'''Kang Tai'''  was a [[Kingdom of Wu|Wu]] Chinese traveller in the middle of the third century.  He is known for his travels to [[Southeast Asia]] in which he became one of the first Chinese, along with [[Zhu Ying]], to document the existence of the [[monarchy|kingdom]] known as [[Kingdom of Funan|Funan]] in Chinese records.<ref>{{cite book|last=Hall|first=D.G.E.|title=A History of South-East Asia, Fourth Edition|year=1981|publisher=Macmillan Education Ltd.|location=Hong Kong|isbn=0-333-24163-0|pages=25}}</ref> He was reportedly impressed with the accomplishments of Funan as well as with its capital city and reported that the written language of Funan bore similarities to Indian script.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tarling|first=Nicholas|title=The Cambridge History of Southeast Asia  Volume 1  Part 1  From early times to c. 1500|year=1999|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, England, United Kingdom|isbn=0-521-66369-5|pages=194}}</ref>

